03:01.374 --> 03:06.322
If I were to tell you a quote from a pastor who was training pastors, he said something like this,

03:07.234 --> 03:12.381
Because of the technological advances of today, your people have ready hands for information.

03:12.481 --> 03:17.388
Thus, we need to be well prepared to stay ahead of the learning curve of the people in the pews.

03:18.830 --> 03:19.992
Well, that just sounds obvious.

03:21.875 --> 03:24.338
Until you consider the fact that was said by Charles Spurgeon.

03:25.700 --> 03:33.651
Spurgeon was saying in the 1800s, that technology is advancing so quickly, we've got to do our best to stay in our study to stay ahead of the people in the pews.

03:33.692 --> 03:35.474
Well, if that was true in the 1800s,

03:36.098 --> 03:37.220
How much more is it true now?

03:37.740 --> 03:41.966
The context in which he said that gives us a little bit more of an understanding.

03:42.026 --> 03:44.289
So here's what's happening when we come to verse one.

03:45.030 --> 03:47.834
We're roughly 850 years before the birth of Christ.

03:47.854 --> 03:53.642
850 years from this point, Jesus will be born in Bethlehem's manger.

03:53.702 --> 03:57.027
So what's happening at this point in Jewish history?

03:57.107 --> 04:02.514
Well, about 100 years prior to this, the nations have divided.

04:03.362 --> 04:09.690
If you remember something about the Jewish history and the Jewish kingdom, for a long time, God was the people's kings.

04:09.710 --> 04:12.313
You had the judges and God was their king.

04:12.353 --> 04:16.439
But during the time of Samuel, the people said, we want to be like all the other people.

04:16.659 --> 04:17.660
We want a king.

04:18.361 --> 04:19.162
So God gave them one.

04:19.603 --> 04:20.364
He gave them Saul.

04:21.265 --> 04:22.707
And Saul reigned for 40 years.

04:23.708 --> 04:28.214
At Saul's death, there was a little bit of turmoil as they were trying to find who was going to be God's choice.

04:28.254 --> 04:31.698
And David stepped in and David reigned for 40 years.

04:32.354 --> 04:41.992
At David's death, a little bit of a struggle between the brothers on who wanted to take control, and David made sure that Nathan and the people knew that Solomon was his choice, and Solomon reigned for 40 years.

04:42.313 --> 04:45.399
Sort of easy to remember the first three kings, they all reigned for 40 years.

04:46.040 --> 04:49.106
Those 120 years are called the United Kingdom.

04:49.826 --> 04:55.453
At the death of Solomon, as you read through the Old Testament, that's when things can sometimes get confusing if we go too fast.

04:55.834 --> 05:02.062
Because all of a sudden, now you're reading about a king of the north and the king of the south, and sometimes they have the same name, and sometimes they have similar names.

05:02.082 --> 05:06.908
And at the death of Solomon, we have Reabbom and Jeroboam, and we have the kingdom divided.

05:07.769 --> 05:12.455
We have the northern kingdom, which is the ten tribes of Israel, their capital city of Samaria.

05:13.236 --> 05:14.578
We have the southern kingdom.

05:14.754 --> 05:17.839
And that's Judah, and their capital city would be Jerusalem.

05:18.239 --> 05:21.164
And there's Benjamin there in Judah, and that's the southern kingdom.

05:21.785 --> 05:26.853
And this divided kingdom has been in existence for about 100 years as we come to Obadiah's day.

05:28.195 --> 05:37.970
When you look at the northern kingdom, reading specifically through the books of first and second kings and first and second chronicles, here's what we learn about the northern kingdom, not one good king.

05:38.978 --> 05:45.044
There's not one good king in Israel where God said, and he did that which was right in the sight of God.

05:45.084 --> 05:47.746
It doesn't happen one time in the northern kingdom.

05:48.487 --> 05:50.369
In the southern kingdom, there's a dynasty.

05:50.469 --> 05:51.830
It's the descendants of David.

05:52.311 --> 05:53.312
They're not all righteous.

05:54.133 --> 05:54.993
They're not all faithful.

05:55.694 --> 05:59.858
But God had made a covenant to David, and so God left David's seed on its own.

06:00.659 --> 06:07.986
And as we come to the time of Obadiah, in the northern kingdom, there's that famous couple we've all heard of, Ahab.

06:08.546 --> 06:09.167
in Jezebel.

06:10.489 --> 06:14.955
And they're ruling and waging war, and there's a prophet in the northern kingdom standing against them.

06:15.576 --> 06:16.597
His name is Elijah.

06:17.719 --> 06:21.264
In the southern kingdom, Jehoshaphat has recently passed off the scene.

06:22.265 --> 06:24.008
Jehoshaphat was a godly king.

06:24.028 --> 06:24.789
He was a good king.

06:24.829 --> 06:25.610
He loved the Lord.

06:25.650 --> 06:27.312
He didn't always make wise decisions.

06:28.273 --> 06:33.160
One of the decisions he made was to marry his son to Ahab's house.

06:34.202 --> 06:37.266
So Jehoram, who's the king during the time of Obadiah,

06:37.826 --> 06:39.868
Mary is a lady named Athaliah.

06:40.509 --> 06:46.274
When you read through the books of the chronicles, she later on usurps the throne and tries to kill the Davidic line.

06:46.334 --> 06:50.218
It's a satanic plot to wipe out God's line from David.

06:50.718 --> 06:53.641
And God spares a little baby, and seven years later he becomes king.

06:54.702 --> 07:00.768
And that's what's happening in the world, Ahab and Jezebel in the north, and Jehoram in the south, and wicked kings all around.

07:00.828 --> 07:03.771
And in the middle of that, God begins to bring judgment.

07:04.471 --> 07:07.154
And as God begins to bring judgment into his people,

07:08.130 --> 07:11.834
There's another nation watching, Edom.

07:13.597 --> 07:22.027
Edom, we may not recognize that name, but we'd probably know the progenitor, the ancestor of that race, his name is Esau.

07:23.909 --> 07:28.935
Esau and Jacob are a story of two brothers that don't get along.

07:30.677 --> 07:32.579
I don't have any brothers, I have two sisters.

07:33.340 --> 07:38.066
We didn't always get along, but I never thought about selling them into slavery.

07:40.098 --> 07:43.282
You read sometimes Jacob and Esau how they're tricking each other.

07:43.302 --> 07:46.347
Then you read about the sons of Jacob and how they're sort of added.

07:46.387 --> 07:48.970
It's a dysfunctional family at times, isn't it?

07:50.372 --> 07:57.161
And yet Esau and Jacob, in those early days, Esau got what the book of Hebrews calls a root of bitterness.

07:58.563 --> 08:00.466
He never got over the fact that he

08:00.546 --> 08:03.450
sold his birthright for a measly pot of soup.

08:03.470 --> 08:04.591
And he never got over that.

08:04.631 --> 08:07.014
And that translated into his descendants.

08:07.034 --> 08:12.441
And years later, it's still Edom and Esau, Edom's descendants, they're still battling it out.

08:13.362 --> 08:18.969
And it reminds us of an ancient brother, brotherly dual years before that, Cain and Abel.

08:20.250 --> 08:22.533
And Cain, when he killed Abel, he tried to hide it.

08:22.553 --> 08:26.418
He asked God a simple question, am I my brother's keeper?

08:27.170 --> 08:33.218
And tonight, as we look at Obadiah, I have entitled tonight's message, yes, you are your brother's keeper.

08:34.280 --> 08:44.313
And when Israel and Judah were being attacked, and we'll come to it in a moment in the book of Second Chronicles, when they were being attacked, Edom was rejoicing, cheering them on, helping them.

08:44.593 --> 08:53.185
And when Judahites were trying to escape, Edom was meeting them at the passes and killing them, or turning them back around and handing them and selling them off as slaves.

08:54.226 --> 08:57.010
And in the book we read here in the book of Obadiah in a moment,

08:57.634 --> 09:02.543
When it came time to sort of split the loot and split the spoil, Eden was right there taking part of it.

09:03.164 --> 09:11.219
They were rejoicing in the downfall of God's people, and so Obadiah steps up and says, now God wants to bring judgment upon you.

09:11.260 --> 09:12.742
This is what's happening.

09:13.504 --> 09:21.138
So another prophet, not Elijah the well-known one, but a small prophet, Obadiah stands up in the middle of difficult times, in the middle of

09:21.410 --> 09:24.954
The Philistines in the middle of the Arab nations coming and attacking his people.

09:25.034 --> 09:31.380
And in the middle of all that, he sees God working in his people and God judging those who were not a friend to Israel.

09:33.022 --> 09:35.704
Reminds us of another covenant in the book of Genesis, doesn't it?

09:36.545 --> 09:39.388
So during this time, we come to Obadiah.

09:39.408 --> 09:42.111
So with that in mind, by way of introduction, let's ask a few questions.

09:42.912 --> 09:43.813
Who is this guy?

09:44.573 --> 09:45.294
Who is Obadiah?

09:45.314 --> 09:48.037
His name means servant or worshiper of the Lord.

09:48.337 --> 09:49.138
That's a good name.

09:49.410 --> 09:50.631
He's a servant of the Lord.

09:50.672 --> 09:51.793
He's a worshiper of the Lord.

09:51.813 --> 09:53.034
He's a worshiper of Jehovah.

09:53.675 --> 09:55.738
Now, Obadiah, he doesn't list his father's name.

09:56.659 --> 10:02.606
When you read a lot of the prophets, this guy, the son of this guy, the son of this guy prophesied to this nation and this king.

10:02.846 --> 10:04.188
You know, oh, I know when this took place.

10:04.248 --> 10:05.129
Pretty easy to identify.

10:06.050 --> 10:08.694
Obadiah doesn't give us those little clues, those little hints.

10:08.714 --> 10:10.476
He's not as forward with it.

10:10.496 --> 10:11.717
We don't know who his father was.

10:11.757 --> 10:14.080
We don't know the kings that are ruling here.

10:15.802 --> 10:18.866
And the name Obadiah would be sort of a common name.

10:19.042 --> 10:21.905
the servant of the Lord would be a common name for God's people.

10:22.706 --> 10:28.173
And so asking who is this Obadiah could sort of be like asking the question, did you read that book, John wrote?

10:28.994 --> 10:29.635
Well, which John?

10:31.016 --> 10:34.701
John living now, John who's lived for like 200 years ago, John's sort of a common name.

10:34.741 --> 10:35.702
It doesn't really help us.

10:35.962 --> 10:37.304
We need a little more information.

10:38.065 --> 10:46.034
And so because of the lack sometimes of information on Obadiah's ancestry and his descendants and the kingdom, sometimes there's this

10:46.210 --> 10:48.193
a debate on when he was written.

10:48.253 --> 10:50.377
Some people say he was written around 850 B.C.

10:50.417 --> 10:53.863
And some say he was written about 580 after the fall of Jerusalem.

10:54.384 --> 11:01.215
And so we're arguing tonight, and that's the reason Obadiah comes first in this series, that Obadiah was written about 850 B.C.

11:02.217 --> 11:02.878
Why is that?

11:03.819 --> 11:07.145
Well, in verse number 17, go ahead and look at that for a moment.

11:08.747 --> 11:12.754
Verse 17, but upon Mount Zion shall be deliverance.

11:13.122 --> 11:17.369
It's an interesting phrase, but here's what I want you to know about, and maybe jot it down in the margin of your notes.

11:18.130 --> 11:20.194
Joel quotes this in Joel 2.32.

11:21.696 --> 11:27.446
Joel was writing about 830 BC, so if Joel is quoting Obadiah, then Obadiah has to be written first.

11:28.127 --> 11:30.511
So we're putting Obadiah as the earliest prophet.

11:30.531 --> 11:35.058
Because he's the first prophet to write, Obadiah is also the first prophet to ever tell us

11:35.138 --> 11:36.760
Something about the day of the Lord.

11:36.780 --> 11:40.184
It'll be a reoccurring theme we hear in the major and minor prophets.

11:40.204 --> 11:43.308
Obadiah is the first one to use that expression as he's writing.

11:43.949 --> 11:45.231
So when did he live?

11:45.531 --> 11:46.012
Who was he?

11:46.052 --> 11:49.096
He's a prophet whose name means name of the Lord, servant of the Lord.

11:49.456 --> 11:50.117
When did he live?

11:50.978 --> 11:56.785
Well, as mentioned between 850 BC, roughly that timeframe, Joel quotes him.

11:57.386 --> 11:59.569
Jeremiah quotes him or alludes to him.

11:59.789 --> 12:01.211
Amos quotes him and alludes to him.

12:01.671 --> 12:03.794
This gives him sort of an early dating.

12:05.346 --> 12:11.536
I've mentioned already the book is written against the nation other than Israel and other than Judah.

12:11.556 --> 12:12.597
It's written about Edom.

12:12.617 --> 12:14.681
So let's do a quick survey of who Edom was.

12:16.303 --> 12:29.644
Not only were they this descendants of Esau, they were the people that in the early days of the Exodus, when God was bringing them out, they asked passage to go through Edom's coast and Edom said, no, no, no, not coming into our coast.

12:29.664 --> 12:31.026
They refused them passage.

12:31.778 --> 12:35.783
And throughout any time, Edom could sort of get an advantage as they wanted to.

12:35.823 --> 12:38.526
And in the days of David, David put him on a subjection.

12:39.287 --> 12:44.013
And you read about this in the reign of David, he made all of the people in Edom to be subject to him.

12:44.073 --> 12:56.127
They were brought under his control, but during the time of Jehorum, which is the time we've mentioned, in Second Chronicles chapter 21 and Second Kings chapter 8, Edom revolts.

12:57.108 --> 12:58.450
They make their own king

12:58.818 --> 13:04.647
and they begin to establish their own independence, and they're sort of raising up themselves against the nation of Israel.

13:06.670 --> 13:09.814
You still see some of the descendants in the New Testament of Edom as well.

13:11.517 --> 13:28.242
By the time we come to the New Testament, they're not quite called Edom, there's a different spelling of the name because we're going through different languages, the Hebrew language is sort of passing off the same, the Greek language is becoming more popular, and it's one of the New Testament they're called Edumier, and so there's this idea of the Edomians.

13:29.122 --> 13:33.687
It doesn't mean a whole lot to us, except we do know one very famous one, Herod.

13:35.069 --> 13:39.754
Herod, who's called the king of Israel during the New Testament, isn't really a Jewish person.

13:40.535 --> 13:41.917
He's a descendant of Edom.

13:42.337 --> 13:43.759
He's a usurper to the throne.

13:44.460 --> 13:56.754
He's an Edomite who's come into the throne there because of his connections, his connections with Rome, and as a result of that, it's causing some problems, and they're looking for a deliverer, a Messiah.

13:57.314 --> 14:06.307
This battle for control of the land of Edom eventually finds these descendants going into a famous city and building high cliffs in the rocks.

14:06.367 --> 14:08.570
And today we know their famous city is Petra.

14:09.331 --> 14:11.013
Perhaps you've seen a picture of Petra.

14:11.073 --> 14:14.378
It's pretty amazing what they do in that stonework in the stone.

14:14.438 --> 14:18.564
You go into this area and there's all this facades there and it's almost impenetrable.

14:18.624 --> 14:20.847
And this is where the Edomites were dwelling.

14:20.867 --> 14:22.770
And today, modern day Jordan.

14:22.978 --> 14:27.764
And they thought that no one could touch them, that no one could harm them.

14:28.004 --> 14:28.945
You could see the pride.

14:29.005 --> 14:31.528
We'll talk about in just a moment as we read these first few verses.

14:32.409 --> 14:34.572
So these Edomite people here.

14:34.932 --> 14:36.554
Well, what's the big idea?

14:36.654 --> 14:38.757
What's going on in the book of Obadiah?

14:38.817 --> 14:41.701
Why is this book being written?

14:41.721 --> 14:42.682
Okay.

14:42.702 --> 14:44.764
Let's turn, if you will, to 2 Chronicles 21.

14:44.784 --> 14:51.112
2 Chronicles 21 will come back to Obadiah in just a moment.

14:51.993 --> 14:52.914
2 Chronicles

14:55.650 --> 14:56.592
chapter number 21.

14:56.872 --> 15:01.580
There's a few things that happened in this chapter that's relevant to the timeframe that we're in.

15:01.640 --> 15:08.391
In the early part of this chapter, verse number one, Jehoshaphat dies.

15:08.631 --> 15:12.878
He sleeps with his father, Johorim, reigns in his stead, verse eight.

15:14.400 --> 15:22.994
In his days, in Johorim's day, this descendant of David, who's not a good king, the Edomites revolted from under the dominion of Judah,

15:23.106 --> 15:24.347
they made themselves a king.

15:24.387 --> 15:28.392
And Johorim went forth with his princes and all his chariots, and he fought against them.

15:28.412 --> 15:33.037
He smote them, but the Edomites, verse 10, revolted from under the hand of Judah unto this day.

15:33.938 --> 15:37.682
Also in verse 10, Libna revolted from them.

15:37.702 --> 15:39.204
And they made high places.

15:39.664 --> 15:45.210
And you're starting to see the Davidic kingdom losing some of its land and some of its prestige.

15:46.192 --> 15:52.018
Verse number 12, Elijah sends a message to the king and basically saying, you need to repent.

15:52.546 --> 16:03.201
Verse 16, the Lord stirs up against Jehoram the spirit of the Philistines, the Arabians that were near the Ethiopians, and they're fighting against Jehoram and against Judah.

16:04.162 --> 16:08.529
And this is when Edom has revolted, and Edom is sort of rejoicing about the fact that other people are attacking.

16:09.310 --> 16:20.786
And the Philistines and the Arabians come into Judah, verse 17, they break into it, they carried all this substance that was in the king's house, and they carried away his wives, there was only one son left out of the nation here.

16:21.474 --> 16:30.245
Then verse 18, because of Jehoram's continual refusal to repent, God brings an incurable disease upon him in verse 18.

16:31.266 --> 16:33.969
Verse 19, he dies after two years with this disease.

16:35.151 --> 16:36.512
The people made no burning for him.

16:37.413 --> 16:39.015
He was 32 years old when it began to rain.

16:39.055 --> 16:40.597
He rained in Jerusalem eight years.

16:41.699 --> 16:43.521
He departed without being desired.

16:44.682 --> 16:48.126
They buried him in the city of David, but not in the sepulchre of the kings.

16:49.688 --> 16:51.090
He was an unwanted king.

16:51.298 --> 16:52.239
an unloved king.

16:52.279 --> 16:55.082
He didn't bring about good things for the people.

16:56.123 --> 16:58.466
And as a result, God begins to bring His judgment in.

16:58.506 --> 17:01.970
